for other connections.

235
00:15:16,395 --> 00:15:20,595
For more marginalized services, or
if you want to embrace full service

236
00:15:20,595 --> 00:15:24,435
approach, you must first refactor
your client and messaging systems

237
00:15:25,125 --> 00:15:29,715
during this refactor, the first thing
to consider is separating the roles.

238
00:15:30,330 --> 00:15:35,370
Processes, you need to clearly separate
the producers from the consumers.

239
00:15:35,700 --> 00:15:40,439
The reason for this is to decouple them
when deployed in the cloud, allowing them

240
00:15:40,439 --> 00:15:45,990
to scale independently and be updated
without dependencies on one another.

241
00:15:46,560 --> 00:15:50,460
For example, if you have a backup
in a queue, you can scale up

242
00:15:50,460 --> 00:15:54,150
your consumers without ramping up
additional producer connections.

243
00:15:56,010 --> 00:15:58,770
You also want to understand
your massive delivery models.

244
00:15:59,340 --> 00:16:02,550
You need to determine whether
you need point-to-point delivery

245
00:16:02,820 --> 00:16:04,560
or a published subscribe model.

246
00:16:05,430 --> 00:16:07,050
The difference between the two is simple.

247
00:16:07,650 --> 00:16:11,250
When a message is sent to a destination,
do you want it to be received

248
00:16:11,250 --> 00:16:13,020
only once by a single consumer?

249
00:16:13,740 --> 00:16:15,870
Or do you want it to
be broadcasted across?

250
00:16:15,900 --> 00:16:18,330
All consumers subscribed
to that designation.

251
00:16:19,200 --> 00:16:22,440
Essentially, it's about whether
the method is processed once

252
00:16:22,440 --> 00:16:24,600
overall or once per consumer.

253
00:16:25,890 --> 00:16:29,460
From an MQ broker perspective,
you can handle both models

254
00:16:29,460 --> 00:16:30,780
within a single infrastructure.

255
00:16:32,130 --> 00:16:36,840
For publish subscribe, you can
use topics or exchanges depending

256
00:16:36,840 --> 00:16:39,150
on whether you use MQ or Rev mq.

257
00:16:40,080 --> 00:16:43,980
MQ Brokers also have queues for
point-to-point interactions, allowing

258
00:16:43,980 --> 00:16:48,870
messages to be processed just once in
a run Robin manner across consumers.

259
00:16:50,324 --> 00:16:56,355
However, when you move to serverless
solutions like Amazon SQS and SNS,

260
00:16:56,685 --> 00:17:01,694
these are two distinct services designed
to handle different delivery models.

261
00:17:02,324 --> 00:17:07,425
Amazon Simple Notification Service
SNS, uses a published subscribe model.

262
00:17:07,845 --> 00:17:12,825
You have a topic, consumers subscribe
to that topic, and all consumers receive

263
00:17:12,825 --> 00:17:14,835
the same message from the producer.

264
00:17:16,080 --> 00:17:21,510
On the other hand, the simple Q Service
SQS uses a point-to-point delivery model,

265
00:17:21,870 --> 00:17:27,450
allowing a message to be received and
processed only once by a single consumer

266
00:17:27,870 --> 00:17:29,940
rather than across all consumers.

267
00:17:31,530 --> 00:17:36,600
Now let's look at some example Python
code for interacting with SQS, and we

268
00:17:36,600 --> 00:17:41,125
will compare it to how we interact with
Web MQ brokers, as I showed you earlier.

269
00:17:42,105 --> 00:17:46,095
First with SQS, there's no
real connection management.

270
00:17:46,485 --> 00:17:51,585
You only need to define or manage the
queues and then send and receive messages.

271
00:17:51,975 --> 00:17:55,004
Because you don't have persistent
connection to manage, you can

272
00:17:55,004 --> 00:17:59,325
focus more directly on the business
logic of handling each message.

273
00:18:00,195 --> 00:18:02,024
To start, you can create a queue.

274
00:18:02,085 --> 00:18:06,855
In SQS using the create queue
method, you define the name and basic

275
00:18:06,855 --> 00:18:11,054
characteristics of the queue, such
as the message retention period.

276
00:18:11,459 --> 00:18:13,500
Text and access policies.

277
00:18:14,669 --> 00:18:17,639
You can then use the queue
name to get the queue handle.

278
00:18:17,939 --> 00:18:21,149
You can also remove the queue
once you have the queue handle

279
00:18:21,600 --> 00:18:23,459
by calling the delete method.

280
00:18:25,230 --> 00:18:29,310
When working as a producer, you send
messages through the send message,

281
00:18:29,310 --> 00:18:34,560
API call you first, get the queue by
its name to access the handle, and

282
00:18:34,560 --> 00:18:36,330
then send a message to that queue.

283
00:18:37,020 --> 00:18:38,730
You define the My body.

284
00:18:39,135 --> 00:18:44,445
And can include various attri attributes
or texts attached to the message

285
00:18:44,595 --> 00:18:47,025
such as trace IDs or other IDs.

286
00:18:48,015 --> 00:18:51,645
On the consumer side, you
use receive message calls to

287
00:18:51,645 --> 00:18:53,385
pull message from the queue,

288
00:18:55,995 --> 00:18:59,535
similar to Rev MQ, where you
have to acknowledge the message

289
00:18:59,985 --> 00:19:01,545
after you receive a message.

290
00:19:01,545 --> 00:19:05,115
In SQS, you have to delete
it using a delete operation.

291
00:19:06,015 --> 00:19:10,515
Once you get the message, you
receive a message handle, which you

292
00:19:10,515 --> 00:19:14,235
use to call the delete operation
to remove it from the queue.

293
00:19:15,075 --> 00:19:19,875
If you do not delete the message, it'll
return to the queue and become visible

294
00:19:19,875 --> 00:19:26,565
again after a certain period of time that
it define when refactoring your client.

295
00:19:26,565 --> 00:19:31,125
To move from a traditional method
broker to services like SQS or

296
00:19:31,125 --> 00:19:34,245
SNS, the first thing to consider
is protocol compatibility.

297
00:19:35,535 --> 00:19:38,535
A typical worker relies on
connection based protocols like

298
00:19:38,595 --> 00:19:41,745
A MQP web sots, or open wire.

299
00:19:42,645 --> 00:19:46,065
But when working with serverless
architectures, the protocol now

300
00:19:46,065 --> 00:19:49,785
becomes H-T-D-P-S or GMS APIs.

301
00:19:50,475 --> 00:19:54,555
These are API based connections,
not persistent connections.

302
00:19:55,155 --> 00:19:59,955
You are making API calls to a
service to send or receive messages.

303
00:20:01,125 --> 00:20:05,415
You also want to consider whether you
need strict message ordering or if you

304
00:20:05,415 --> 00:20:10,035
can sacrifice a little bit of other
preservation for higher scalability.

305
00:20:10,635 --> 00:20:17,205
For example, SQS offers standard cues
and FIFA first in first out queues.

306
00:20:17,655 --> 00:20:18,435
FIFA cues.

307
00:20:18,645 --> 00:20:22,780
Maintain the exact order of messages
while standard queues, provide

308
00:20:22,890 --> 00:20:26,595
best effort ordering, but allow
you to scale almost infinitely.

309
00:20:28,170 --> 00:20:32,700
Additionally, because these are serverless
architectures built within the cloud

310
00:20:32,730 --> 00:20:35,370
ecosystem, you gain much more visibility.

311
00:20:36,060 --> 00:20:39,780
For example, you can enable cloud
trial to lock all data requests.

312
00:20:40,320 --> 00:20:45,000
This give you a detailed request
level look to see when the message

313
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:50,460
was sent, when it was received,
the origin IP address, and the user

314
00:20:50,460 --> 00:20:54,045
roles involved allowing for far
better tracking and monitoring.

315
00:20:55,080 --> 00:21:00,120
Furthermore, because these are native
AWS services, they integrate easily

316
00:21:00,240 --> 00:21:06,149
with IAM or IAM, identity Center for
Authentication and authorization.

317
00:21:06,750 --> 00:21:12,990
In contrast with Rev mq, even if
hosted on Amazon MQ service, you might

318
00:21:12,990 --> 00:21:19,169
have to set up an LDAP server rather
than I am users or roles for the same

319
00:21:19,260 --> 00:21:21,840
authentication and authorization purpose.

320
00:21:23,610 --> 00:21:28,020
There are some limitations to be
aware of the migrating to SQS or SNS.

321
00:21:28,679 --> 00:21:29,460
For example.

322
00:21:29,730 --> 00:21:34,710
There's a default payload limitation of
up to one megabytes from message sites.

323
00:21:35,010 --> 00:21:38,940
However, you can get around
this by using Java or Python

324
00:21:38,940 --> 00:21:40,620
library extensions built by AWS.

325
00:21:41,475 --> 00:21:46,125
Which allow you to have massive
message bodies up to two gigabytes by

326
00:21:46,125 --> 00:21:49,155
utilizing the S3 service on the backend.

327
00:21:49,905 --> 00:21:54,825
What this means is that when you send
a message through SQS or SNS, instead

328
00:21:54,825 --> 00:21:59,985
of sending the entire payload, the
library uploads the message object to

329
00:21:59,985 --> 00:22:05,350
an S3 bucket, and only sends a pointer
to that object within your message.

330
00:22:06,300 --> 00:22:10,320
Producer transfers the pointer
as a message to the consumer,

331
00:22:10,650 --> 00:22:14,970
effectively increasing your message
size limit from my one megabytes

332
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:16,545
all the way up to two gigabytes.

333
00:22:19,185 --> 00:22:22,155
Those are some key factors to
consider the migrating your

334
00:22:22,155 --> 00:22:23,505
message system to the cloud.

335
00:22:23,985 --> 00:22:28,215
You need to understand the technologies
to see if there are any limitations,

336
00:22:28,425 --> 00:22:32,055
constraints or changes compared
to your current environment.

337
00:22:32,735 --> 00:22:37,115
You also need to plan how you will
handle authentication and authorization.

338
00:22:37,595 --> 00:22:41,855
Your clients still need to engage
with the service, so understanding

339
00:22:41,855 --> 00:22:46,355
the available security method
is critical to ensuring seamless

340
00:22:46,355 --> 00:22:48,395
integration with the current systems.

341
00:22:49,295 --> 00:22:51,695
You also want to consider
the deployment settings.

342
00:22:52,235 --> 00:22:55,265
When deploying on-prem, you
have complete customization.

343
00:22:56,024 --> 00:23:00,165
Once you move to managed services,
certain configurations are taken

344
00:23:00,195 --> 00:23:04,155
out of your deployment settings and
managed entirely by the service itself.

345
00:23:05,175 --> 00:23:08,595
Lastly, you need to understand
how you want to operate

346
00:23:08,925 --> 00:23:10,605
and monitoring the service.

347
00:23:11,340 --> 00:23:14,880
On-prem messaging systems, you
can connect directly to the

348
00:23:14,880 --> 00:23:17,220
server to get a full set of data.

349
00:23:17,820 --> 00:23:21,990
But in a cloud environment, it usually
depend on monitoring services like

350
00:23:22,020 --> 00:23:26,910
CloudWatch, utilizing matrix and
logging to manage and monitor the

351
00:23:26,910 --> 00:23:28,025
health of your messaging system.

352
00:23:30,090 --> 00:23:32,250
That brings us to the
end of the presentation.

353
00:23:32,760 --> 00:23:36,300
Hopefully you now have a better
understanding of the migration process.

354
00:23:36,330 --> 00:23:37,620
From on-prem to the cloud.

355
00:23:38,370 --> 00:23:42,570
We cover the overall benefits of
migrating to a serverless architecture,

356
00:23:42,840 --> 00:23:47,520
the different pathways for migration,
and the fact that migration requires

357
00:23:47,520 --> 00:23:52,530
both application level changes like code
modifications and adjustments to how you

358
00:23:52,530 --> 00:23:55,290
operate at business and operational level.

359
00:23:55,950 --> 00:23:56,250
Thank you.

